---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;

const PLAYBOOK_BASE =
  "https://wenhaoyu-bryan.github.io/AI-PM-Operating-Playbook/en/workbench/";
---

<Layout
  title={`Loop Engineering — ${config.site.title}`}
  description="Designing the feedback loops through which an AI product, its team, and its delivery artifacts improve over repeated iterations."
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />

  <Main
    pageTitle="Loop Engineering for AI Product Development"
    class="app-prose"
  >
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      Loop Engineering is a personal working concept, not an established
      industry term. It describes a practical way to design the feedback loops
      through which an AI product, its team, and its delivery artifacts improve
      over repeated iterations. If harness engineering defines the environment
      for a single agent run, loop engineering defines how that environment
      evolves.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">
      Why One-Shot Prompting Is Insufficient
    </h2>
    <p>
      A single prompt to an AI agent produces a first draft — of code, of a
      spec, of a prototype. First drafts are useful, but they are never the
      final product. AI products improve through iteration: each cycle adds
      knowledge, corrects errors, and narrows the gap between what exists and
      what is needed.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      The problem is that most teams use AI tools without designing their
      iteration process. They prompt, get output, and move on. The output does
      not feed back into the next cycle. Knowledge stays in someone's head
      instead of in artifacts the system can use. This is what loop engineering
      addresses.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">The Product Loop</h2>
    <p>The highest-level loop spans the entire product development cycle:</p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>Idea</strong> &rarr; <strong>Structured Framing</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Prototype</strong> &rarr; <strong>Evaluation</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Feedback</strong> &rarr; <strong>Updated Context</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Next Iteration</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      Each pass through this loop should produce artifacts: a refined PRD, a
      more accurate prototype, evaluation results, updated constraints. Without
      artifacts, the loop resets to zero every time.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">The Implementation Loop</h2>
    <p>
      At the code level, the implementation loop is what coding agents naturally
      do:
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>Code Generation</strong> &rarr; <strong>Test</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Review</strong> &rarr; <strong>Fix</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Commit</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      This loop works when the agent has good test coverage and clear feedback.
      It fails when tests are missing, error messages are vague, or the agent is
      fixing the wrong thing. The harness (context, tools, constraints)
      determines how tight this loop runs.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">The Evaluation Loop</h2>
    <p>
      AI products need evaluation that goes beyond traditional QA. The
      evaluation loop measures product quality, not just code correctness:
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>Metrics</strong> &rarr; <strong>Measurement</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Analysis</strong> &rarr; <strong>Adjustment</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      For an AI product, this might mean tracking output accuracy, user
      acceptance rate, hallucination frequency, or task completion rate. The key
      is that evaluation results become input to the next iteration — they
      update the context, constraints, or acceptance criteria.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">The User-Feedback Loop</h2>
    <p>
      User feedback is the external signal that tells you whether the product
      loops are converging on something valuable:
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>Usage</strong> &rarr; <strong>Observation</strong> &rarr;
      <strong>Insight</strong> &rarr; <strong>Product Update</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      This loop is the slowest and the most important. It connects the internal
      development loops to external reality. A product team that runs fast
      internal loops but ignores user feedback is optimizing for the wrong
      thing.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">The Context Update Loop</h2>
    <p>
      Every loop produces learnings. The context update loop captures those
      learnings and makes them available to the next iteration:
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>Learnings</strong> &rarr; <strong>Updated Project Docs</strong>
      &rarr; <strong>Better Next Iteration</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      This is where the CLAUDE.md pattern, project READMEs, and structured
      handoff documents matter. They are the mechanism by which accumulated
      knowledge persists across sessions, team members, and agent invocations.
      Without this loop, every iteration starts from the same baseline.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Artifacts Produced by Each Loop</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Product loop:</strong> refined PRDs, updated roadmaps, evaluation
        reports, user research notes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Implementation loop:</strong> code commits, test results, PR reviews,
        bug reports.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evaluation loop:</strong> metric dashboards, comparison reports, quality
        trend data.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>User-feedback loop:</strong> usage analytics, support tickets, user
        interview summaries, feature requests.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Context update loop:</strong> updated CLAUDE.md, refined architecture
        docs, revised conventions, knowledge base entries.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">
      The value of loop engineering is not any single artifact — it is that each
      artifact becomes input to the next cycle. Orphaned artifacts are wasted
      work.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Failure Modes</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Loops that do not close.</strong> The team generates output but never
        feeds results back. Each iteration starts from scratch.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Feedback that is ignored.</strong> Evaluation or user feedback exists
        but does not change behavior. The team repeats the same patterns expecting
        different outcomes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Context that goes stale.</strong> Project documentation reflects an
        earlier state of the product. The agent makes decisions based on outdated
        information.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Optimizing the wrong loop.</strong> The team runs fast implementation
        loops but has no evaluation loop. They ship quickly but ship the wrong thing.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">
      Connection to AI PM Operating Playbook
    </h2>
    <p>
      The AI PM Operating Playbook's Evaluation and Risk step is a direct
      application of the evaluation loop. It helps PMs define what to measure,
      how to measure it, and what to do with the results. The generated
      artifacts — evaluation plans, risk assessments, acceptance criteria — are
      designed to feed back into subsequent iterations.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 mb-8">
      <a
        href={PLAYBOOK_BASE}
        class="bg-accent text-accent-foreground inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >
        Build an evaluation and feedback plan in AI PM Operating Playbook ↗
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/harness-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Harness Engineering
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/vibe-coding")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Vibe Coding for Product Discovery
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/ai-native-prd")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          AI-Native PRD
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Playbook Index
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
